sols_latex:
We saw from
{part
a)} that we have the series expansion

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{1+x^3}=1-x^3+x^6-x^9+\ldots
\end{align*} and so we can write that

\begin{align*}
\int_0^{0.1} \frac{1}{1+x^3}\,dx &= \int_0^{0.1} dx - \int_0^{0.1} x^3\,dx +\int_0^{0.1} x^6\,dx - \int_0^{0.1} x^9\,dx +\ldots\\
&= 0.1 - \frac{(0.1)^4}{4} + \frac{(0.1)^7}{7} - \frac{(0.1)^{10}}{10} + \ldots
\end{align*}
where the \emph{n}\textsuperscript{th} term is

\begin{align*}
\frac{(-1)^n(0.1)^{3n+1}}{3n+1}
\end{align*} Since this is an alternating
sequence which converges to zero, we have that the error when neglecting
everything past the \emph{n}\textsuperscript{th} term. Thus

\begin{align*}
|\textrm{error}| &\leq \left| \frac{(-1)^n(0.1)^{3n+1}}{3n+1} \right| \\&= \frac{0.1^{3n+1}}{3n+1} \\&= \frac{10^{-(3n+1)}}{3n+1}
\end{align*}
if we want this to be less than 10\textsuperscript{-9}, then we can
choose \emph{n} = 3, where the error will be less than

\begin{align*}
\frac{10^{(-9+1)}}{9+1}=10^{-11}
\end{align*} which works fine since it is
clearly even less than 10\textsuperscript{-9}.

statement_latex:
Use part (a) to determine an approximation of the following definite
integral

\begin{align*}
\int_0^{0.1} \frac{1}{1+x^3}dx
\end{align*} so that the error in the
approximation satisfies

\begin{align*}
|\text{error}| \leq 10^{-9}
\end{align*} Remember to justify your answer.
